4 A BILL FOR AN ACT ENTITLED: “AN ACT ESTABLISHING THE MONTANA HUNTERS FIRST ACT;
5 CREATING A STUDY OF IMPACTS ON MONTANA'S HUNTING SEASONS RELATED TO BLOCK
6 MANAGEMENT, SEASON STRUCTURE, AND RESIDENT AND NONRESIDENT LICENSE ALLOCATION;
7 ASSIGNING RESPONSIBILITY FOR THE STUDY TO THE DEPARTMENT OF FISH, WILDLIFE, AND
8 PARKS; DEFINING THE SCOPE OF THE STUDY; REQUIRING A PUBLISHED REPORT THAT INCLUDES
9 RECOMMENDATIONS; AND ; PROVIDING EFFECTIVE DATES; PROVIDING A TERMINATION DATE.”
10
11 WHEREAS, there has been a steady growth in nonresident hunting license sales and hunting pressure
12 on publicly accessible lands; and
13 WHEREAS, Montana’s significant population growth necessitates a detailed assessment of hunting
14 season structure after 40 years; and
15 WHEREAS, there has been a decline of roughly 1 million acres in the amount of private land enrolled in
16 the block management program over the past 10 years, concentrating hunters on smaller amounts of publicly
17 accessible lands; and
18 WHEREAS, hunter success rates have been steadily falling, while hunter use days have been steadily
19 increasing; and
20 WHEREAS, public sentiment indicates that Montana’s wildlife resources are being strained by a variety
21 of factors; and
22 WHEREAS, landowner fatigue with the current hunting season structure relative to elk hunting
23 opportunities is setting in; and
24 WHEREAS, the wildlife of Montana belongs to all citizens; and
25 WHEREAS, the process of finding solutions to the issues surrounding the current management of
26 hunting seasons, including resident and nonresident license allocation, should include all stakeholders.
27
28 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF THE STATE OF MONTANA:
- 1 - LC 1323

